# Terraform Command Safety

Applies when Terraform/OpenTofu configuration is in context (see globs). See `agent-cli-core.mdc` for piping, intent, and autonomy rules.

## Policy wording

- The **agent MUST NOT execute** the commands listed in the **NEVER run** section below—**no exceptions** (including user approval). The **human** runs apply/destroy/state surgery in their own shell or in **CI/CD** after merge.
- **DO NOT** format them as **runnable steps for the user inside the agent chat** (numbered “run this now”); you **MAY** name them only in **documentation** (runbooks, what CI runs, narrative “then a human/ pipeline runs …”).
- **Prefer execution via CI/CD pipelines** (plan/apply in automation after merge) rather than the agent simulating apply—aligns with GitOps and PR-driven workflow.
- **When apply or destroy is required:** agent changes **`.tf` / modules in Git** → show **`terraform plan`** / `-refresh-only` / saved-plan narrative → **PR** → human or pipeline **`apply`**/**`destroy`** outside the agent.

## NEVER run — destructive / state-changing Terraform CLI

**NEVER run** the following from the **agent** terminal. Treat **`terraform state rm`** and **`terraform state mv`** as **especially dangerous**: no plan preview; misuse **silently corrupts state**.

- `terraform apply`, `terraform destroy`
- `terraform state rm`
- `terraform state mv`
- `terraform taint`, `terraform untaint`
- `terraform force-unlock`
- `terraform import`

## `terraform init` (non-destructive but sensitive)

- **`terraform init`** is normal setup (providers, modules, backend wiring) and is **not** equivalent to apply/destroy.
- **Warn** when the user or context implies **`terraform init -upgrade`** (can pull newer provider versions → behavior drift).
- **Warn** when **backend configuration** changed or is newly introduced (can alter **where state lives**—high blast radius).

## Planning and apply hygiene

- Prefer **`terraform plan -out=<file>`** for a **reproducible** artifact. When explaining apply workflows, prefer **`terraform apply <saved-plan-file>`** (applying a **previously saved** plan) instead of **`terraform apply`** that implicitly **re-plans at apply time**—harder to shortcut and clearer what will run.
- Use **`terraform plan -refresh-only`** when investigating **drift** **without** proposing normal resource changes (state/refresh lens only; good debugging path).
- **Re-run `terraform plan`** (or refresh the saved plan) **before any apply** when explaining human-operated flows—detects drift when reality diverges from the last plan.
- Avoid **manual changes in cloud consoles (“clickops”)**—they are a primary cause of **drift** between **state** and **real infrastructure**.

## Preferred read-only / non-destructive suggestions

`terraform plan`, `terraform plan -refresh-only`, `terraform validate`, `terraform fmt`, `terraform fmt -check`, `terraform show`, `terraform output`, `terraform state list`, `terraform state show`, `terraform providers`, `terraform graph`, and similar **non-mutating** inspection commands.
